Here's a function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text:
```c++
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <iostream>
#include <boost/algorithm/string/replace.hpp>

std::string convertToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::vector<std::string> tokens;
    boost::replace_all(markdown, "\\[", "<strong>");
    boost::replace_all(markdown, "\\[/", "</strong>");
    boost::replace_all(markdown, "\\[list config\\]", "<ul>");
    boost::replace_all(markdown, "\\[list item\\]", "<li>");
    boost::replace_all(markdown, "\\[list item\\](.+?)\\[list item\\]", "<li><a href=\"#\">$1</a></li>");
    boost::replace_all(markdown, "\\[list item\\]", "</ul>");
    tokens.push_back(markdown);

    std::string html = "<pre>";
    for (const std::string& token : tokens) {
        html += token;
    }
    html += "</pre>";
    return html;
}
```
This function uses the `boost::replace_all` function to replace certain patterns in the `markdown` string with HTML formatted text. It splits the resulting string into tokens and appends them to a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text. The resulting HTML string is then returned as the result of the function.

